#Text=County Dublin
#Text=County Dublin ( Irish : Contae Bhaile Átha Cliath ) is a historic county surrounding Dublin city in the Republic of Ireland .
#Text=It was abolished as an administrative or political unit in 1994 , with its territory allocated to three new counties .

#Text=Nevertheless it still coheres as a destination for travellers , in two ways : for the city to escape to the surrounds , eg to the seaside at Howth or the races at Leopardstown ; and for visitors to stay here and day-trip into Dublin while avoiding the city 's congestion and high prices .
#Text=Cities and towns
#Text=The former county now comprises the City of Dublin , the County of Fingal to the north , South County to the south-west and Dún Laoghaire-Rathdown County on the south coast .

#Text=, Ireland 's capital city , is a wonderful destination , packed with top museums , galleries , eating places . . . why even the jail is a must-see , as the nation 's revolutionary patriots were to discover .
#Text=County Fingal lies to the north of the city .
#Text=is centre of this new county .
#Text=Dublin Airport is here .
#Text=is on the coast just east of Swords .
#Text=is a small beach resort with a golf course .
#Text=is a seaside resort ; just offshore is the uninhabited Ireland 's Eye .
#Text=is a small commuter town .
#Text=is a small town with a notable church , round tower and ( amazingly ) a vineyard .
#Text=is a former fishing village , now a commuter town .
#Text=is at the north end of the county near to Drogheda .
#Text=South County is actually to the south-west ; it 's modern commuterland ( eg around Tallaght ) and lacks historic townships and visitor attractions .
#Text=Dún Laoghaire-Rathdown County to the south has :
#Text=is the former port , now a quiet seaside town with a large marina .
#Text=has Italian-style villas and a couple of Norman turrets , plus boat trips to Dalkey Island .
#Text=is a " city-within-a-city " on Belfield Campus .
#Text=is across the border into County Wicklow , but within the County Dublin transport system and a natural extension to the city .
#Text=Climate
#Text=The city and county have a mild climate moderated by the Atlantic , so they are year-round destinations .
#Text=It seldom snows or freezes hard nowadays , though winter Nov-Feb sees overnight frosts .
#Text=Summers are cool , around 19°C ( 66°F ) in July and August .
#Text=The area is not particularly wet - its average annual rainfall of 732.7mm ( 28.8 in ) is less than London - but light showers are frequent .

#Text=It 's glorious when the sun shines but unless at some point in your trip you 've spent 15 minutes sheltering under a shop awning on Grafton Street with cold rain dripping down your neck , wondering if it 's too early to go the pub , you have n't really experienced Dublin .
#Text=Get in
#Text=is 10 km north of downtown Dublin , and has excellent connections across Europe and to North America .
#Text=It 's within the town of Swords near the M1 / M50 junction , so it 's accessible for all road routes across Ireland , and many inter-city buses run to the airport .
#Text=Dublin Port has frequent ferries from Liverpool , Holyhead on Anglesey Wales , and the Isle of Man .
#Text=Ferries from Fishguard in Wales and Cherbourg in Normandy sail to Rosslare , with train connections to Dublin .
#Text=The former port at Dún Laoghaire is no longer used .
#Text=For touring the north , another ferry connection is from Cairnryan near Stranraer in Scotland to Belfast then drive or bus south .
#Text=Trains from all over Ireland converge on Dublin , some making edge-of-city stops so you may not have to go into central Dublin then travel out again .
#Text=Trains from Sligo , Belfast , Drogheda and the coast south to Rosslare come into Connolly Station north of the river ; most local trains across County Dublin also come here .
#Text=All other long-distance trains ( eg from Cork , Limerick & Galway ) come into Heuston 3 km west of the centre .
#Text=Allow 45 mins if you need to change stations , and get a ticket made out for Dublin city centre so the tram ride from Heuston is included .
#Text=Get around
#Text=See Dublin for transport options including the Leap Card , valid for buses and DART trains across the county .

#Text=Trains within this fare zone run from Dublin Connolly south along the coast to Dún Laoghaire , Greystones and Kilcoole , north along the coast to Howth , Malahide and Balbriggan , and inland to Drumcondra , Maynooth and Kilcock ; and from Dublin Heuston they run west to Sallins and Naas .
#Text=Car rental : Dublin Airport has the best choice and rates .
#Text=That 's wrong side of the city for the south , so a city-centre rental might work better .
#Text=See
#Text=Castles ranging from the grand ( Dublin ) , rich ( Malahide ; perhaps Howth whenever it reopens ) and scrappy ( Swords , and Bremore in Balbriggan ) .
#Text=Plus various mock-castellations , stumpy little turrets and redoubts , and the coast is dotted with Martello Towers , built within sight of each other .
#Text=Killiney — Climb Killiney Hill and see the stunning views out around the bay and to Dalkey Island .

#Text=Blackrock — Walk along the strand , visit the famed Blackrock market , a flea market open on weekends and bank holidays , and have a drink at O'Rourke 's , the old haunt of the Irish author Flann O'Brien .
#Text=Serviced by the DART and the 4 , 4A , 5 , 45 , 7 , and 8 buses .
#Text=Flavours of Fingal agricultural show and food & drink fair is held annually at the end of June at Newbridge House & Farm , Donabate north of Swords .
#Text=Flower shows are held across the county mid-July through August , various venues .
#Text=Do
#Text=Boat trips to the little islands nearby :
#Text=Dalkey Island , Ireland 's Eye off Howth , and Lambay Island off Skerries .
#Text=You can also take a boat cruise between Howth and Dún Laoghaire .
#Text=Go to the races at Leopardstown , in the southern suburbs of Dublin .
#Text=It has meetings all year , flat-racing in summer and jumps ( " National Hunt " ) in winter .
#Text=St Patrick 's Day is celebrated worldwide and especially here .
#Text=In 2020 it falls on Tue 17 March .
#Text=Many towns around the county will have parades , and in Dublin there will be a 4-day event , details not yet announced .
#Text=Eat
#Text=The county has many popular resturants and pubs .
